{"cursor":"3608","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"'Senior citizen' is a common polite designation for an elderly person in both UK\nand US English, and it implies or means that the person is retired. http://www.oup.com/oald-\nbin/web_getald7index1a.pl http://www.bartleby.com/61/36/S0263600.html-\nhttp://www.chambersharrap.co.uk/chambers/features/chref/chref.py/mai-\nn?query=senior+citizen&title=21st http://dictionary.cambridge.org/def-\nine.asp?key=71747&dict=CALD This in turn usually implies or in fact means\nthat the person is over the retirement age, which varies according to country.\nSynonyms include 'pensioner' in UK English and 'retiree' and 'senior' in US\nEnglish. Some dictionaries describe widespread usage of \"senior citizen\" for\npeople over the age of 65. http://www.ldoceonline.com/dictionary/senior-\ncitizen \"Senior citizen\" is replacing the term 'old-age pensioner'\ntraditionally used in UK English. http://www.oup.com/oald-\nbin/web_getald7index1a.pl\n\nWhen defined in an official context, senior citizen is often used for legal or\npolicy-related reasons in determining who is eligible for certain benefits\navailable to the age group.\n\nIt is used in general usage instead of traditional terms such as old person, old-\nage pensioner, or elderly as a courtesy and to signify continuing relevance of\nand respect for this population group as \"citizens\" of society, of senior\nrank. http://books.google.com/books?id=xylg46v5fRUC&pg=PA64&lpg=PA64 Mental\nHealth Concepts by Claire G. Waughfield, Teresa S. Burckhalter\n\nThe term was apparently coined in 1938 during a political\ncampaign. http://www.theseniortimes.com/richler.htm The Senior Times\nIt has come into widespread use in recent decades in legislation, commerce, and\ncommon speech. Especially in less formal contexts, it is often abbreviated as\n\"senior(s)\", which is also used as an adjective.\n\nIn commerce, some businesses offer customers of a certain age a \"senior\ndiscount\". The age at which these discounts are available vary between 55, 60 or\n65, and other criteria may also apply. Sometimes a special \"senior discount\ncard\" or other proof of age needs to be obtained and produced to show\nentitlement.\n","linknr":141,"url":"Senior_citizens","recorded":1371244362,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Senior_citizen&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Senior_citizen&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","/wiki/Senior_citizen","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","/w/index.php?title=Senior_citizens&redirect=no","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/Old_age","#cite_note-1","#cite_note-2","#cite_note-3","#cite_note-4","/wiki/Retirement_age","#cite_note-5","#cite_note-6","/wiki/Citizen","#cite_note-7","#cite_note-8","/wiki/Adjective","/wiki/Senior_discount","/wiki/Senior_discount_card","#Qualifying_age","#See_also","#References","#References_2","/w/index.php?title=Senior_citizen&action=edit&section=1","/wiki/Pension","/wiki/Marketing","/wiki/United_States","#cite_note-9","/wiki/AARP","/w/index.php?title=Senior_citizen&action=edit&section=2","/wiki/Old_age","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/4/4a/Commons-logo.svg/30px-Commons-logo.svg.png","//commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/Category:Senior_citizens","/w/index.php?title=Senior_citizen&action=edit&section=3","#cit